# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boron-carbide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] An isomer of 1,2-dimethyldiborane is 1,1-dimethyldiborane, known as unsymmetrical dimethyldiborane, which has two methyl groups on one boron atom.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Other methylated versions of diborane including methyldiborane, trimethyldiborane, tetramethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Instead of hydrogen chloride, methyl iodide or trimethylsilyl chloride can be used.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Lithium methylborohydride can be made by treating methylboronic esters with lithium aluminium hydride.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Methylboranes arise the reaction of diborane and trimethylborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] This reaction produces 1-methyldiborane, 1,1-dimethyldiborane, 1,1,2-trimethyldiborane, and 1,1,2,2-tetramethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] By treating monomethyldiborane with ether, dimethyl ether borane (CH3)2O.BH3 leaving methylborane which rapidly dimerises to 1,2-dimethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Tetramethyl lead reacts with diborane to give a range of methyl-substituted diboranes, ending up at trimethylborane, but including 1,1-dimethyldiborane, and trimethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Other products are hydrogen gas and lead metal.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Other methods to form methyldiboranes include treating hydrogen with trimethylborane between 80 and 200 °C under pressure, or treating a metal borohydride with trimethylborane in the presence of hydrogen chloride, aluminium chloride or boron trichloride.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] If the borohydride is sodium borohydride, then methane is a side product.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] If the metal is lithium, then no methane is produced. dimethylchloroborane and methyldichloroborane are also produced as gaseous products.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] When Cp2Zr(CH3)2 reacts with diborane, a borohydro group inserts into the zirconium-carbon bond, and methyl diboranes are produced.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] 1,2-Dimethyldiborane is produced by the room temperature disproportionation of trimethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Gas chromatography can be used to determine the amounts of the methyl boranes in a mixture.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] The order of elution are: diborane, monomethyldiborane, trimethylborane, 1,1-dimethyldiborane, 1,2-dimethyldiborane, trimethyldiborane, and last tetramethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] The nuclear resonance shift for the bridge hydrogen is 9.55 ppm for the unsymmetrical isomer and 9.73 ppm for the symmetrical isomers, compared to 10.49 for diborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Methylborane shows little tendency to disproportionate (redistribute) at room temperature.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] It reacts stepwise with alkenes to produce mono and dialkylmethylboranes.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] More methylated boranes are less stable.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] 1,2-Dimethyldiborane slowly converts to 1,1-dimethyldiborane.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Symmetrical dimethyldiborane reacts with trimethylamine to yield a solid adduct trimethylamine-methylborane (CH3)3N·BH2CH3.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] When dimethyldiborane is combined with ammonia and heated, B-methyl borazoles are produced.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] These borazoles can have one, two or three methyl groups substituted on the boron atoms.
[src:boron-carbide/1-2-dimethyldiborane] Under normal conditions dimethyldiborane does not react with hydrogen.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:boron-carbide/abrasives] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide is prepared by direct reaction of aluminium and carbon in an electric arc furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] An alternative reaction begins with alumina, but it is less favorable because of generation of carbon monoxide.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Silicon carbide also reacts with aluminium to yield Al4C3.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] This conversion limits the mechanical applications of SiC, because Al4C3 is more brittle than SiC.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide hydrolyses with evolution of methane and considerable amounts of heat.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] The addition of 10g of Al4C3 to 10g of water was found to reach a maximum temperature of 387 °F (197 °C) at a time of 11 minutes in one study, while in another the addition of 20g of Al4C3 to 10g of water reached a maximum temperature of 280 °F (138 °C).
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Reversing the order and adding 10g of water to 20g of Al4C3 reached a maximum temperature of 349 °F (176 °C).
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] This tendency can be decreased by coating the silicon carbide particles with a suitable oxide or nitride, preoxidation of the particles to form a silica coating, or using a layer of sacrificial metal.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] An aluminium-aluminium carbide composite material can be made by mechanical alloying, by mixing aluminium powder with graphite particles.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide has an unusual crystal structure that consists of alternating layers of Al2C and Al2C2.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Each aluminium atom is coordinated to 4 carbon atoms to give a tetrahedral arrangement.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Carbon atoms exist in 2 different binding environments; one is a deformed octahedron of 6 Al atoms at a distance of 217 pm.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] The other is a distorted trigonal bipyramidal structure of 4 Al atoms at 190–194 pm and a fifth Al atom at 221 pm.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Small amounts of aluminium carbide are a common impurity of technical calcium carbide.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In electrolytic manufacturing of aluminium, aluminium carbide forms as a corrosion product of the graphite electrodes.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In metal matrix composites based on aluminium matrix reinforced with non-metal carbides (silicon carbide, boron carbide, etc.) or carbon fibres, aluminium carbide often forms as an unwanted product.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] In case of carbon fibre, it reacts with the aluminium matrix at temperatures above 500 °C (932 °F); better wetting of the fibre and inhibition of chemical reaction can be achieved by coating it with e.g. titanium boride.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide particles finely dispersed in aluminium matrix lower the tendency of the material to creep, especially in combination with silicon carbide particles.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] Aluminium carbide can be used as an abrasive in high-speed cutting tools.
[src:boron-carbide/aluminium-carbide] It has approximately the same hardness as topaz.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:boron-carbide/american-society-for-testing-materials] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Reaction of diborane with ammonia mainly gives the diammoniate salt [H2B(NH3)2]+[BH4]− (diammoniodihydroboronium tetrahydroborate).
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The initially formed ammonium borohydride [NH4]+[BH4]− is unstable and dehydrogenates under ambient conditions to form ammonia borane.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] These processes are generally higher yielding and produce less boron-containing byproducts than those performed with borane or its adducts.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The most common solvents used for this process are polar aprotic solvents such as tetrahydrofuran or 1,4-dioxane, in which both sodium borohydride and most ammonium salts are only weakly soluble.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The presence of water or methanol can improve the solubility of the reagents and accelerate the process but competing hydrolysis or methanolysis of the intermediate leads to the undesirable formation of boric acid or trimethyl borate.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The molecule adopts a structure similar to that of ethane, with which it is isoelectronic.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The B−H and N−H distances are 1.15 and 0.96 Å, respectively.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Its similarity to ethane is tenuous since ammonia borane is a solid and ethane is a gas: their melting points differing by 284 °C.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] This difference is consistent with the highly polar nature of ammonia borane.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The H atoms attached to boron are hydridic (negatively charged) and those attached to nitrogen are acidic (positively charged).
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The structure of the solid indicates a close association of the N*H* and the B*H* centers.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The closest H−H distance is 1.990 Å, which can be compared with the H−H bonding distance of 0.74 Å.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] This interaction is called a dihydrogen bond.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The original crystallographic analysis of this compound reversed the assignments of B and N.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The updated structure was arrived at with improved data using the technique of neutron diffraction that allowed the hydrogen atoms to be located with greater precision.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Ammonia borane has been suggested as a storage medium for hydrogen, e.g. for when the gas is used to fuel motor vehicles.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] It can be made to release hydrogen on heating, being polymerized first to (NH2BH2)*n*, then to (NHBH)*n*, which ultimately decomposes to boron nitride (BN) at temperatures above 1000 °C.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] It is more hydrogen-dense than liquid hydrogen and also able to exist at normal temperatures and pressures.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Ammonia borane finds some use in organic synthesis as an air-stable derivative of diborane.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] It can be used as a reducing agent in transfer hydrogenation reactions, often in the presence of a transition metal catalyst.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] The first amine adduct of borane was derived from trimethylamine.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Borane tert-butylamine complex is prepared by the reaction of sodium borohydride with t-butylammonium chloride.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Generally adducts are more robust with more basic amines.
[src:boron-carbide/ammonia-borane] Variations are also possible for the boron component, although primary and secondary boranes are less common.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:boron-carbide/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] An **electric arc furnace** (**EAF**) is a furnace that heats material by means of an electric arc.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Industrial arc furnaces range in size from small units of approximately one-tonne capacity (used in foundries for producing cast iron products) up to about 400-tonne units used for secondary steelmaking.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Arc furnaces used in research laboratories and by dentists may have a capacity of only a few dozen grams.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Industrial electric arc furnace temperatures can reach 1,800 °C (3,300 °F), while laboratory units can exceed 3,000 °C (5,400 °F).
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In electric arc furnaces, the material inside the furnace (referred to as a charge) is directly exposed to an electric arc, and the current from the electrode terminals passes through the charge material.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Arc furnaces differ from induction furnaces, which use eddy currents to heat the charge.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In the 19th century, a number of people had employed an electric arc to melt iron.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The possibility of using an electric arc to melt metals was demonstrated by Vasily Vladimirovich Petrov in 1803.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Sir Humphry Davy conducted an experimental demonstration in 1810; welding was investigated by William Haseldine Pepys in 1815; Pinchon attempted to create an electrothermic furnace in 1853; and, in 1878–79, Sir William Siemens took out patents for electric furnaces of the arc type.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The first successful and operational furnace was invented by James Burgess Readman in Edinburgh, Scotland, in 1888 and patented in 1889.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This was specifically for the creation of phosphorus.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Further electric arc furnaces were developed by Paul Héroult, of France, with a commercial plant established in the United States in 1907.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The Sanderson brothers formed The Sanderson Brothers Steel Co. in Syracuse, New York, installing the first electric arc furnace in the U.S.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This furnace is now on display at Station Square, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Initially "electric steel" produced by an electric arc furnace was a specialty product for such uses as machine tools and spring steel.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Arc furnaces were also used to prepare calcium carbide for use in carbide lamps.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The *Stassano electric furnace* is an arc type furnace that usually rotates to mix the bath.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The *Girod furnace* is similar to the *Héroult furnace*.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] While EAFs were widely used in World War II for production of alloy steels, it was only later that electric steelmaking began to expand.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Steel, for low-cost, carbon steel "long products" (structural steel, rod and bar, wire, and fasteners) in the U.S. market.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] As of January 2022, Nucor was one of the largest steel producers in the US.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] It entered the market for long steel products in 1969, using a mini-mill with an EAF as its steelmaking furnace, which was soon followed by other manufacturers.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] While Nucor expanded rapidly in the Eastern US, the companies that followed them into mini-mill operations concentrated on local markets for long products, where the EAF allowed the plants to vary production according to local demand.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This pattern was followed globally, with EAF steel production primarily used for long products, while integrated mills, using blast furnaces and basic oxygen furnaces, cornered the markets for "flat products"—sheet steel and heavier steel plate.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In 1987, Nucor expanded into the flat products market, still using the EAF production method.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] An electric arc furnace used for steelmaking consists of a refractory-lined vessel, usually water-cooled in larger sizes, covered with a retractable roof, and through which one or more graphite electrodes enter the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The hearth may be hemispherical in shape, or in an eccentric bottom tapping furnace (see below), the hearth has the shape of a halved egg.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In modern meltshops, the furnace is often raised off the ground floor, so that ladles and slag pots can easily be maneuvered under either end of the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Separate from the furnace structure is the electrode support and electrical system, and the tilting platform on which the furnace rests.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Two configurations are possible: the electrode supports and the roof tilt with the furnace, or are fixed to the raised platform.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A typical alternating current furnace is powered by a three-phase electrical supply, and therefore has three electrodes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Electrodes are round in section, and typically in segments with threaded couplings, so that as the electrodes wear, new segments can be added.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The arc forms between the charged material and the electrode; the charge is heated both by current passing through the charge and by the radiant energy evolved by the arc.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The electric arc temperature reaches around 3,000 °C (5,400 °F), thus causing the lower sections of the electrodes to glow incandescently when in operation.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The electrodes are automatically raised and lowered by a positioning system, which may use either electric winch hoists or hydraulic cylinders.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The regulating system maintains approximately constant current and power input during the melting of the charge, even though scrap may move under the electrodes as it melts.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The mast arms holding the electrodes can either carry heavy busbars (which may be hollow water-cooled copper pipes carrying current to the electrode clamps) or be "hot arms", where the whole arm carries the current, increasing efficiency.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Hot arms can be made from copper-clad steel or aluminium.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Large water-cooled cables connect the bus tubes or arms with the transformer located adjacent to the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The transformer is installed in a vault and is cooled by pump-circulated transformer oil, with the oil being cooled by water via heat exchangers.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The furnace is built on a tilting platform so that the liquid steel can be poured into another vessel for transport.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The operation of tilting the furnace to pour molten steel is called "tapping".
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Originally, all steelmaking furnaces had a tapping spout closed with refractory that washed out when the furnace was tilted, but often modern furnaces have an eccentric bottom tap-hole (EBT) to reduce inclusion of nitrogen and slag in the liquid steel.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] These furnaces have a taphole that passes vertically through the hearth and shell, and is set off-centre in the narrow "nose" of the egg-shaped hearth.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] It is filled with refractory sand, such as olivine, when it is closed off.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Modern plants may have two shells with a single set of electrodes that can be transferred between the two; one shell preheats scrap while the other shell is utilised for meltdown.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Other DC-based furnaces have a similar arrangement, but have electrodes for each shell and one set of electronics.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] AC furnaces usually exhibit a pattern of hot and cold-spots around the hearth perimeter, with the cold-spots located between the electrodes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Modern furnaces mount oxygen-fuel burners in the sidewall and use them to provide chemical energy to the cold-spots, making the heating of the steel more uniform.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A mid-sized modern steelmaking furnace would have a transformer rated about 60,000,000 volt-amperes (60 MVA), with a secondary voltage between 400 and 900 volts and a secondary current in excess of 44,000 amperes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In a modern shop such a furnace would be expected to produce a quantity of 80 tonnes of liquid steel in approximately 50 minutes from charging with cold scrap to tapping the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In comparison, basic oxygen furnaces can have a capacity of 150–300 tonnes per batch, or "heat", and can produce a heat in 30–40 minutes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Enormous variations exist in furnace design details and operation, depending on the end product and local conditions, as well as ongoing research to improve furnace efficiency.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The largest scrap-only furnace (in terms of tapping weight and transformer rating) is a DC furnace operated by Tokyo Steel in Japan, with a tap weight of 420 tonnes and fed by eight 32 MVA transformers for 256 MVA total power.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] To produce a ton of steel in an electric arc furnace requires approximately 400 kilowatt-hours (1.44 gigajoules) per short ton or about 440 kWh (1.6 GJ) per tonne.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The theoretical minimum amount of energy required to melt a tonne of scrap steel is 300 kWh (1.09 GJ) (melting point 1,520 °C (2,768 °F)).
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Therefore, a 300-tonne, 300 MVA EAF will require approximately 132 MWh of energy to melt the steel, and a "power-on time" (the time that steel is being melted with an arc) of approximately 37 minutes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Electric arc steelmaking is only economical where there is plentiful, reliable electricity, with a well-developed electrical grid.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In many locations, mills operate during off-peak hours when utilities have surplus power generating capacity and the price of electricity is less.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This compares very favourably with energy consumption of global steel production by all methods estimated at some 5,555 kWh (20 GJ) per tonne (1 gigajoule is equal to approximately 278 kWh).
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Scrap metal is delivered to a scrap bay, located next to the melt shop.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Scrap generally comes in two main grades: shred (whitegoods, cars and other objects made of similar light-gauge steel) and heavy melt (large slabs and beams), along with some direct reduced iron (DRI) or pig iron for chemical balance.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The scrap is loaded into large buckets called baskets, with "clamshell" doors for a base.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Care is taken to layer the scrap in the basket to ensure good furnace operation; heavy melt is placed on top of a light layer of protective shred, on top of which is placed more shred.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] These layers should be present in the furnace after charging.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] After loading, the basket may pass to a scrap pre-heater, which uses hot furnace off-gases to heat the scrap and recover energy, increasing plant efficiency.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The scrap basket is then taken to the melt shop, the roof is swung off the furnace, and the furnace is charged with scrap from the basket.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Charging is one of the more dangerous operations for the EAF operators.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A lot of potential energy is released by the tonnes of falling metal; any liquid metal in the furnace is often displaced upwards and outwards by the solid scrap, and the grease and dust on the scrap is ignited if the furnace is hot, resulting in a fireball erupting.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In some twin-shell furnaces, the scrap is charged into the second shell while the first is being melted down, and pre-heated with off-gas from the active shell.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Other operations are continuous charging—pre-heating scrap on a conveyor belt, which then discharges the scrap into the furnace proper, or charging the scrap from a shaft set above the furnace, with off-gases directed through the shaft.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Other furnaces can be charged with hot (molten) metal from other operations.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] After charging, the roof is swung back over the furnace and meltdown commences.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The electrodes are lowered onto the scrap, an arc is struck and the electrodes are then set to bore into the layer of shred at the top of the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Lower voltages are selected for this first part of the operation to protect the roof and walls from excessive heat and damage from the arcs.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Once the electrodes have reached the heavy melt at the base of the furnace and the arcs are shielded by the scrap, the voltage can be increased and the electrodes raised slightly, lengthening the arcs and increasing power to the melt.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This enables a molten pool to form more rapidly, reducing tap-to-tap times.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Oxygen is blown into the scrap, combusting or cutting the steel, and extra chemical heat is provided by wall-mounted oxygen-fuel burners.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Both processes accelerate scrap meltdown.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Supersonic nozzles enable oxygen jets to penetrate foaming slag and reach the liquid bath.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] An important part of steelmaking is the formation of slag, which floats on the surface of the molten steel.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Slag usually consists of metal oxides, and acts as a destination for oxidised impurities, as a thermal blanket (stopping excessive heat loss) and helping to reduce erosion of the refractory lining.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For a furnace with basic refractories, which includes most carbon steel-producing furnaces, the usual slag formers are calcium oxide (CaO, in the form of burnt lime) and magnesium oxide (MgO, in the form of dolomite and magnesite).
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] These slag formers are either charged with the scrap, or blown into the furnace during meltdown.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Another major component of EAF slag is iron oxide from steel combusting with the injected oxygen.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Later in the heat, carbon (in the form of coke or coal) is injected into this slag layer, reacting with the iron oxide to form metallic iron and carbon monoxide gas, which then causes the slag to foam, allowing greater thermal efficiency, and better arc stability and electrical efficiency.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The slag blanket also covers the arcs, preventing damage to the furnace roof and sidewalls from radiant heat.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Once the initial scrap charge has been melted down, another bucket of scrap can be charged into the furnace, although EAF development is moving towards single-charge designs.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The scrap-charging and meltdown process can be repeated as many times as necessary to reach the required heat weight – the number of charges is dependent on the density of scrap; lower-density scrap means more charges.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] After all scrap charges have completely melted, refining operations take place to check and correct the steel chemistry and superheat the melt above its freezing temperature in preparation for tapping.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] More slag formers are introduced and more oxygen is blown into the bath, burning out impurities such as silicon, sulfur, phosphorus, aluminium, manganese, and calcium, and removing their oxides to the slag.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Removal of carbon takes place after these elements have burnt out first, as they have a greater affinity for oxygen.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Metals that have a poorer affinity for oxygen than iron, such as nickel and copper, cannot be removed through oxidation and must be controlled through scrap chemistry alone, such as introducing the direct reduced iron and pig iron mentioned earlier.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A foaming slag is maintained throughout, and often overflows the furnace to pour out of the slag door into the slag pit.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Temperature sampling and chemical sampling take place via automatic lances.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Oxygen and carbon can be automatically measured via special probes that dip into the steel, but for all other elements, a "chill" sample — a small, solidified sample of the steel — is analysed on an arc-emission spectrometer.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Once the temperature and chemistry are correct, the steel is tapped out into a preheated ladle through tilting the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For plain-carbon steel furnaces, as soon as slag is detected during tapping the furnace is rapidly tilted back towards the deslagging side, minimising slag carryover into the ladle.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For some special steel grades, including stainless steel, the slag is poured into the ladle as well, to be treated at the ladle furnace to recover valuable alloying elements.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] During tapping some alloy additions are introduced into the metal stream, and more fluxes such as lime are added on top of the ladle to begin building a new slag layer.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Often, a few tonnes of liquid steel and slag is left in the furnace in order to form a "hot heel", which helps preheat the next charge of scrap and accelerate its meltdown.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] During and after tapping, the furnace is "turned around": the slag door is cleaned of solidified slag, the visible refractories are inspected and water-cooled components checked for leaks, and electrodes are inspected for damage or lengthened through the addition of new segments.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The taphole is filled with sand at the completion of tapping.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For a 90-tonne, medium-power furnace, the whole process will usually take about 60–70 minutes from the tapping of one heat to the tapping of the next (the tap-to-tap time).
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The furnace is completely emptied of steel and slag on a regular basis so that an inspection of the refractories can be made and larger repairs made if necessary.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] As the refractories are often made from calcined carbonates, they are extremely susceptible to hydration from water, so any suspected leaks from water-cooled components are treated extremely seriously, beyond the immediate concern of potential steam explosions.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Excessive refractory wear can lead to breakouts, where the liquid metal and slag penetrate the refractory and furnace shell and escape into the surrounding areas.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The use of EAFs allows steel to be made from a 100% scrap metal feedstock.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This greatly reduces the energy required to make steel when compared with primary steelmaking from ores.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Another benefit is flexibility: while blast furnaces cannot vary their production by much and can remain in operation for years at a time, EAFs can be rapidly started and stopped, allowing the steel mill to vary production according to demand.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Although steelmaking arc furnaces generally use scrap steel as their primary feedstock, if hot metal from a blast furnace or direct-reduced iron is available economically, these can also be used as furnace feed.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] As EAFs require large amounts of electrical power, many companies schedule their operations to take advantage of off-peak electricity pricing.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A typical steelmaking arc furnace is the source of steel for a mini-mill, which may make bars or strip product.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Mini-mills can be sited relatively near the markets for steel products, so the transport requirements are less than for an integrated mill, which would commonly be sited near a harbor for better access to shipping.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Although the modern electric arc furnace is a highly efficient recycler of steel scrap, operation of an arc furnace shop can have adverse environmental effects.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Since EAF steelmaking mainly use recycled materials like scrap iron and scrap steel, as their composition varies the resulting EAF slag and EAF dust can be toxic.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] EAF dust is collected by air pollution control equipment.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] It is called collected dust and usually contains heavy metals, such as zinc, lead and dioxins, etc.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] It is categorized as hazardous industrial waste and disposal is regulated.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Because of the very dynamic quality of the arc furnace load, power systems may require technical measures to maintain the quality of power for other customers; flicker and harmonic distortion are common power system side-effects of arc furnace operation.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For steelmaking, direct current (DC) arc furnaces are used, with a single electrode in the roof and the current return through a conductive bottom lining or conductive pins in the base.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The advantage of DC is lower electrode consumption per ton of steel produced, since only one electrode is used, as well as less electrical harmonics and other similar problems.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The size of DC arc furnaces is limited by the current carrying capacity of available electrodes, and the maximum allowable voltage.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Maintenance of the conductive furnace hearth is a bottleneck in extended operation of a DC arc furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In a steel plant, a ladle furnace (LF) is used to maintain the temperature of liquid steel during processing after tapping from EAF or to change the alloy composition.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The ladle is used for the first purpose when there is a delay later in the steelmaking process.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The ladle furnace consists of a refractory roof, a heating system, and, when applicable, a provision for injecting argon gas into the bottom of the melt for stirring.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Unlike a scrap melting furnace, a ladle furnace does not have a tilting or scrap-charging mechanism.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Electric arc furnaces are also used for production of calcium carbide, ferroalloys, and other non-ferrous alloys, and for production of phosphorus.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Furnaces for these services are physically different from steel-making furnaces and may operate on a continuous, rather than batch, basis.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Continuous-process furnaces may also use paste-type, Søderberg electrodes to prevent interruptions from electrode changes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Such a furnace is known as a submerged arc furnace, because the electrode tips are buried in the slag/charge, and arcing occurs through the slag, between the matte and the electrode.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The casing and casing fins of the electrode melt the electrode paste through electrical current passing through the electrode casing and heat from the furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A steelmaking arc furnace, by comparison, arcs in the open.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The key is the electrical resistance, which is what generates the heat required: the resistance in a steelmaking furnace is the atmosphere, while in a submerged-arc furnace, the slag (or charge) supplies the resistance.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The liquid metal formed in either furnace is too conductive to form an effective heat-generating resistance.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Smaller arc furnaces may be adequately cooled by circulation of air over structural elements of the shell and roof, but larger installations require intensive forced cooling to maintain the structure within safe operating limits.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The furnace shell and roof may be cooled either by water circulated through pipes which form a panel, or by water sprayed on the panel elements.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Tubular panels may be replaced when they become cracked or reach their thermal stress life cycle.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Spray cooling is the most economical and is the highest efficiency cooling method.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A spray cooling piece of equipment can be relined almost endlessly.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Equipment that lasts 20 years is the norm.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] While a tubular leak is immediately noticed in an operating furnace due to the pressure loss alarms on the panels, at this time there exists no immediate way of detecting a very small volume spray cooling leak.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] These typically hide behind slag coverage and can hydrate the refractory in the hearth, leading to a break out of molten metal or in the worst case a steam explosion.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A plasma arc furnace (PAF) uses plasma torches instead of graphite electrodes.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Each of these torches has a casing with a nozzle and axial tubing for feeding a plasma-forming gas (either nitrogen or argon) and a burnable cylindrical graphite electrode within the tubing.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Such furnaces can be called plasma arc melt (PAM) furnaces; they are used extensively in the titanium-melting industry and similar specialty metal industries.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Vacuum arc remelting (VAR) is a secondary remelting process for vacuum refining and manufacturing of ingots with improved chemical and mechanical homogeneity.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In critical military and commercial aerospace applications, material engineers commonly specify VIM-VAR steels.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] VIM means vacuum induction melted and VAR means vacuum arc remelted.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] VIM-VAR steels become bearings for jet engines, rotor shafts for military helicopters, flap actuators for fighter jets, gears in jet or helicopter transmissions, mounts or fasteners for jet engines, jet tail hooks and other demanding applications.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Most grades of steel are melted once and are then cast or teemed into a solid form prior to extensive forging or rolling to a metallurgically-sound form.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In contrast, VIM-VAR steels go through two more highly purifying melts under vacuum.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] After melting in an electric arc furnace and alloying in an argon oxygen decarburization vessel, steels destined for vacuum remelting are cast into ingot molds.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The solidified ingots then head for a vacuum induction melting furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This vacuum remelting process rids the steel of inclusions and unwanted gases while optimizing the chemical composition.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] The VIM operation returns these solid ingots to the molten state in the contaminant-free void of a vacuum.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This tightly controlled melt often requires up to 24 hours.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Still enveloped by the vacuum, the hot metal flows from the VIM furnace crucible into giant electrode molds.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] A typical electrode is about 15 feet (5 m) tall and will be in various diameters.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For VIM-VAR steels, the surface of the cooled electrodes must be ground to remove surface irregularities and impurities before the next vacuum remelt.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Then the ground electrode is placed in a VAR furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] In a VAR furnace, the steel gradually melts drop-by-drop in the vacuum-sealed chamber.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Vacuum arc remelting further removes lingering inclusions to provide superior steel cleanliness and remove gases like oxygen, nitrogen and hydrogen.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Controlling the rate at which these droplets form and solidify ensures a consistency of chemistry and microstructure throughout the entire VIM-VAR ingot, making the steel more resistant to fracture or fatigue.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] This refinement process is essential to meet the performance characteristics of parts like a helicopter rotor shaft, a flap actuator on a military jet, or a bearing in a jet engine.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For some commercial or military applications, steel alloys may go through only one vacuum remelt, namely the VAR.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] For example, steels for solid rocket cases, landing gears, or torsion bars for fighting vehicles typically involve one vacuum remelt.
[src:boron-carbide/arc-furnace] Vacuum arc remelting is also used in production of titanium and other metals which are reactive or in which high purity is required.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide was first noticed by Henri Moissan (Nobel Prize of chemistry in 1906) in 1894 as a by-product of reactions involving metal borides, but its chemical formula was unknown.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] It was not until the 1930s that the chemical composition was estimated as B4C.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] These features argued against a very simple exact B4C empirical formula.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Because of the B12 structural unit, the chemical formula of "ideal" boron carbide is often written not as B4C, but as B12C3, and the carbon deficiency of boron carbide described in terms of a combination of the B12C3 and B12CBC units.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide has a complex crystal structure typical of icosahedron-based borides.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] There, B12 icosahedra form a rhombohedral lattice unit (space group: *R3m* (No.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] 166), lattice constants: *a* = 0.56 nm and *c* = 1.212 nm) surrounding a C-B-C chain that resides at the center of the unit cell, and both carbon atoms bridge the neighboring three icosahedra.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] This structure is layered: the B12 icosahedra and bridging carbons form a network plane that spreads parallel to the *c*-plane and stacks along the *c*-axis.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] The lattice has two basic structure units – the B12 icosahedron and the B6 octahedron.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Because of the small size of the B6 octahedra, they cannot interconnect.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Instead, they bond to the B12 icosahedra in the neighboring layer, and this decreases bonding strength in the *c*-plane.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Because of the B12 structural unit, the chemical formula of "ideal" boron carbide is often written not as B4C, but as B12C3, and the carbon deficiency of boron carbide described in terms of a combination of the B12C3 and B12C2 units.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Some studies indicate the possibility of incorporation of one or more carbon atoms into the boron icosahedra, giving rise to formulas such as (B11C)CBC = B4C at the carbon-heavy end of the stoichiometry, but formulas such as B12(CBB) = B14C at the boron-rich end.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] "Boron carbide" is thus not a single compound, but a family of compounds of different compositions.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] A common intermediate, which approximates a commonly found ratio of elements, is B12(CBC) = B6.5C.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide is known as a robust material having extremely high hardness (about 9.5 up to 9.75 on Mohs hardness scale), high cross section for absorption of neutrons (i.e. good shielding properties against neutrons), stability to ionizing radiation and most chemicals.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Its Vickers hardness (38 GPa), elastic modulus (460 GPa) and fracture toughness (3.5 MPa·m1/2) approach the corresponding values for diamond (1150 GPa and 5.3 MPa·m1/2).
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] As of 2015, boron carbide is the third hardest substance known, after diamond and cubic boron nitride, earning it the nickname "black diamond".
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide is a semiconductor, with electronic properties dominated by hopping-type transport.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] The energy band gap depends on composition as well as the degree of order.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] The band gap is estimated at 2.09 eV, with multiple mid-bandgap states which complicate the photoluminescence spectrum.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide was first synthesized by Henri Moissan in 1894 by reduction of boron trioxide either with carbon or magnesium in presence of carbon in an electric arc furnace.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] If magnesium is used, the reaction can be carried out in a graphite crucible, and the magnesium byproducts are removed by treatment with acid.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] The property of boron carbide to absorb neutrons without forming long-lived radionuclides makes it an attractive neutron radiation shielding or absorbing material, such as in use for control rods in nuclear power reactors.
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Nuclear applications of boron carbide include shielding and reaction regulation (control rod).
[src:boron-carbide/boron-carbide] Boron carbide filaments exhibit auspicious prospects as reinforcement elements in resin and metal composites, attributed to their exceptional strength, elastic modulus, and low density characteristics.
